1
00:00:01,543 --> 00:00:03,337
[door closes]

2
00:00:03,378 --> 00:00:05,422
[instrumental music]

3
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:22,898
[coughing]

4
00:00:47,339 --> 00:00:48,590
Hey.

5
00:00:49,717 --> 00:00:50,843
Oliver?

6
00:00:57,016 --> 00:00:58,433
You're that vigilante.

7
00:01:02,396 --> 00:01:04,481
Easy, Dig. You were poisoned.

8
00:01:04,523 --> 00:01:06,191
Son of a bitch.

9
00:01:12,447 --> 00:01:16,827
I could have taken you anywhere,
I could have taken you home.

10
00:01:16,869 --> 00:01:19,413
I brought you here.

11
00:01:19,454 --> 00:01:21,122
You really did lose your mind
on that island.

12
00:01:21,164 --> 00:01:22,708
Found a couple things
along the way.

13
00:01:22,750 --> 00:01:24,919
- Like what, archery classes?
- Clarity.

14
00:01:26,879 --> 00:01:29,297
Starling City..

15
00:01:29,339 --> 00:01:32,217
...is dying.

16
00:01:32,259 --> 00:01:36,430
It is being poisoned
by a criminal elite

17
00:01:36,471 --> 00:01:40,225
who don't care who they hurt

18
00:01:40,267 --> 00:01:42,603
as long as they maintain
their wealth and power.

19
00:01:42,644 --> 00:01:44,312
What are you gonna do?

20
00:01:44,354 --> 00:01:46,231
Take 'em all down
by your lonesome?

21
00:01:46,273 --> 00:01:47,441
No.

22
00:01:50,069 --> 00:01:52,738
No, I want you to join me.

23
00:01:52,780 --> 00:01:54,573
Special forces
out of Kandahar.

24
00:01:54,615 --> 00:01:57,534
It's perfect.

25
00:01:57,576 --> 00:01:58,660
You're a fellow soldier.

26
00:01:58,702 --> 00:02:00,537
Oliver, you're not a soldier.

27
00:02:02,081 --> 00:02:03,415
You're a criminal.

28
00:02:05,667 --> 00:02:07,086
And a murderer.

29
00:02:07,127 --> 00:02:09,337
[music continues]

30
00:02:13,508 --> 00:02:16,011
[theme music]

31
00:02:33,946 --> 00:02:35,363
Where were you?

32
00:02:36,615 --> 00:02:37,658
What?

33
00:02:39,576 --> 00:02:40,786
What are you doing here?

34
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:42,370
I heard about the shooting,
and I wanted to

35
00:02:42,412 --> 00:02:44,039
make sure you were okay.

36
00:02:44,081 --> 00:02:45,958
You did?

37
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:47,960
Yeah.

38
00:02:48,002 --> 00:02:49,628
I knocked on the door,
and I found a family

39
00:02:49,670 --> 00:02:51,379
terrified for you.

40
00:02:51,421 --> 00:02:52,798
They had no idea where you were.

41
00:02:52,840 --> 00:02:54,133
Oh.

42
00:02:54,173 --> 00:02:56,093
Oliver, are you so self-centered

43
00:02:56,135 --> 00:02:58,345
that you don't think
that people who care about you

44
00:02:58,386 --> 00:03:01,098
are gonna wonder where you
are after you all got shot at?

45
00:03:01,140 --> 00:03:03,058
You're right.

46
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:05,894
I made peace with your
selfishness a long time ago

47
00:03:07,146 --> 00:03:09,397
but Moira, Thea, and Walter

48
00:03:09,439 --> 00:03:11,441
they don't deserve that.

49
00:03:11,483 --> 00:03:13,610
They deserve better.

50
00:03:13,652 --> 00:03:15,988
Someone who doesn't care
only about himself.

51
00:03:20,909 --> 00:03:22,243
Laurel.

52
00:03:27,206 --> 00:03:29,292
Thank you for coming.

53
00:03:29,334 --> 00:03:31,545
I care about the lives
of other people, Oliver.

54
00:03:33,088 --> 00:03:35,674
Maybe you should try it
sometime.

55
00:03:35,716 --> 00:03:37,342
[instrumental music]

56
00:03:41,930 --> 00:03:43,807
Oh, man.

57
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:47,227
That was harsh.

58
00:03:48,979 --> 00:03:50,939
You okay?

59
00:03:50,981 --> 00:03:53,817
Sure.

60
00:03:53,859 --> 00:03:55,736
Second time tonight,
that a friend of mine

61
00:03:55,777 --> 00:03:58,947
has taken me to the woodshed.

62
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:00,991
It kind of tires you out.

63
00:04:01,033 --> 00:04:02,367
Yeah.

64
00:04:02,409 --> 00:04:03,785
Goodnight.

65
00:04:27,350 --> 00:04:29,686
[bird chirping]

66
00:04:29,728 --> 00:04:32,856
<i>Shengcun.</i>

67
00:04:32,898 --> 00:04:35,442
What am I supposed
to do with that?

68
00:04:35,483 --> 00:04:37,652
<i>Shengcun.</i>

69
00:04:37,694 --> 00:04:40,280
Does that mean "Bird"?

70
00:04:40,321 --> 00:04:42,950
-<i>Shengcun!</i>
- I don't speak Chinese!

71
00:04:53,043 --> 00:04:56,337
I'm sorry, Laurel.
I'm so sorry.

72
00:04:58,215 --> 00:05:00,175
[breathing heavily]

73
00:05:02,343 --> 00:05:04,012
(man on TV)
'There were no signs
of forced entry'

74
00:05:04,054 --> 00:05:05,931
'or any evidence
of a struggle'

75
00:05:05,973 --> 00:05:08,349
'but hours later, the police
found a bloodstained'

76
00:05:08,391 --> 00:05:10,185
'kitchen knife in the trunk..'

77
00:05:10,227 --> 00:05:11,895
Couldn't sleep, either?

78
00:05:11,937 --> 00:05:14,022
No.

79
00:05:14,064 --> 00:05:15,816
What are you watching?

80
00:05:15,857 --> 00:05:18,526
- Peter Declan.
- Hm?

81
00:05:18,568 --> 00:05:21,571
A guy who killed his wife.

82
00:05:21,613 --> 00:05:25,700
Right, this guy killed his wife
in their baby's room.

83
00:05:25,742 --> 00:05:27,202
Psycho.

84
00:05:27,244 --> 00:05:29,746
Camille was everything to me.

85
00:05:29,788 --> 00:05:32,749
I couldn't kill her anymore
than I could kill myself.

86
00:05:32,791 --> 00:05:34,251
And why can't you sleep?

87
00:05:35,627 --> 00:05:37,212
Bad dreams.

88
00:05:37,254 --> 00:05:39,214
About?

89
00:05:39,256 --> 00:05:41,340
Laurel.

90
00:05:41,382 --> 00:05:43,342
So why don't you make a play?

91
00:05:43,384 --> 00:05:45,053
I mean, she did come over here

92
00:05:45,095 --> 00:05:47,055
just to make sure
you didn't get shot.

93
00:05:49,057 --> 00:05:51,977
- There are reasons.
- Mm, what are they?

94
00:05:52,019 --> 00:05:54,395
Besides, you sleeping
with her sister

95
00:05:54,437 --> 00:05:57,524
and her sister dying,
and her father hating your guts

96
00:05:57,565 --> 00:06:00,194
and you basically,
being a jerk to everybody

97
00:06:00,235 --> 00:06:02,821
since you've been back?

98
00:06:02,863 --> 00:06:04,906
Those are the top ones.

99
00:06:08,785 --> 00:06:11,412
I know that it might not seem
like it sometimes, but..

100
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:13,207
[instrumental music]

101
00:06:15,792 --> 00:06:18,377
...I'm not the same person
I used to be.

102
00:06:18,419 --> 00:06:20,922
So show her.

103
00:06:20,964 --> 00:06:22,381
Be yourself.

104
00:06:22,423 --> 00:06:24,676
I mean your new self.

105
00:06:36,688 --> 00:06:38,315
How did you sleep?

106
00:06:38,357 --> 00:06:41,442
- Just fine. Thank you.
- Hm.

107
00:06:41,484 --> 00:06:43,778
- We have a visitor.
- Hm.

108
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:45,697
Mr. Diggle's replacement.

109
00:06:47,157 --> 00:06:48,700
Replacement?

110
00:06:48,742 --> 00:06:52,537
Yes. He tendered his resignation
this morning.

111
00:06:52,579 --> 00:06:54,122
Did he say why?

112
00:06:54,164 --> 00:06:55,916
He said he didn't approve
of the way you spend

113
00:06:55,957 --> 00:06:57,292
your evenings.

114
00:06:57,334 --> 00:06:58,835
Particularly given that
they always begin

115
00:06:58,877 --> 00:07:00,295
with you ditching him.

116
00:07:01,922 --> 00:07:03,673
- Hi.
- Mr. Queen.

117
00:07:03,715 --> 00:07:05,967
Rob Scott.
I'll be your new body man.

118
00:07:06,009 --> 00:07:07,552
That's a firm grip
you got there, Rob.

119
00:07:07,594 --> 00:07:10,889
That's five years SWAT
with Monument Point MCU.

120
00:07:10,931 --> 00:07:12,473
I feel safer already.

121
00:07:12,515 --> 00:07:13,975
Ah, thank God,
we don't have to hear

122
00:07:14,017 --> 00:07:16,311
about this awful man anymore.

123
00:07:18,897 --> 00:07:22,650
'Declan's execution is set
for midnight two days from now.'

124
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:25,570
'Camille Declan's former
employer, Jason Brodeur'

125
00:07:25,612 --> 00:07:27,530
'released a statement
saying, quote'

126
00:07:27,572 --> 00:07:30,784
'"I hope this gives Camille
the peace she deserves."'

127
00:07:30,825 --> 00:07:33,870
- Jason Brodeur?
- What?

128
00:07:33,912 --> 00:07:37,498
The dead wife worked
for Jason Brodeur.

129
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:39,542
Apparently so. What..

130
00:07:39,584 --> 00:07:40,668
Why?

131
00:07:40,710 --> 00:07:41,753
No reason.

132
00:07:41,795 --> 00:07:43,880
Say, Rob, I wanna go into town.

133
00:07:43,922 --> 00:07:45,465
Could you please
get the car for me?

134
00:07:45,506 --> 00:07:47,301
No offense, Mr. Queen,
but I have been filled in

135
00:07:47,342 --> 00:07:49,594
on your tendency
to slip the leash.

136
00:07:49,636 --> 00:07:51,012
If it's all the same to you,
I'd prefer

137
00:07:51,054 --> 00:07:52,847
keeping you in my sights
at all times.

138
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:56,810
We're 20 miles from the city.

139
00:07:56,851 --> 00:07:58,645
If you don't drive me

140
00:07:58,686 --> 00:08:00,397
how else am I gonna get there?

141
00:08:02,523 --> 00:08:03,691
Right?

142
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:10,782
I like him.

143
00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:12,451
[instrumental music]

144
00:08:12,492 --> 00:08:14,035
[bike revving]

145
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:20,750
Hey!

146
00:08:26,173 --> 00:08:27,590
<i>(Oliver)
They say Peter Declan</i>

147
00:08:27,632 --> 00:08:29,801
<i>murdered his wife in
cold blood.</i>

148
00:08:29,843 --> 00:08:31,552
<i>He had no alibi.</i>

149
00:08:31,594 --> 00:08:33,721
<i>And all the evidence
pointed toward it.</i>

150
00:08:33,763 --> 00:08:37,600
<i>He was tried, convicted,
sentenced to death.</i>

151
00:08:37,642 --> 00:08:41,229
<i>An open-and-shut case,
except for one thing.</i>

152
00:08:41,271 --> 00:08:44,565
<i>Declan's wife, Camille
worked for Jason Brodeur.</i>

153
00:08:44,607 --> 00:08:48,069
<i>And Jason Brodeur
is on the list.</i>

154
00:08:53,408 --> 00:08:54,409
Mr. Brodeur.

155
00:08:54,451 --> 00:08:56,870
Admiring your handiwork, Ankov.

156
00:08:58,579 --> 00:09:00,540
You should have just let me
kill both of 'em.

157
00:09:00,581 --> 00:09:02,667
Peter Declan
is worth more alive.

158
00:09:02,709 --> 00:09:05,170
"Husband kills wife"
is a much better headline

159
00:09:05,212 --> 00:09:09,132
than "Whistle-blower uncovers
toxic dumping," don't you think?

160
00:09:09,174 --> 00:09:12,802
Either way, 48 hours,
all this'll be over.

161
00:09:18,308 --> 00:09:20,018
<i>(Oliver)
The odds are good
that Brodeur is involved</i>

162
00:09:20,060 --> 00:09:21,811
<i>in this woman's murder,
which means</i>

163
00:09:21,853 --> 00:09:25,482
<i>an innocent man
is facing execution.</i>

164
00:09:25,524 --> 00:09:28,235
<i>He'll need a good attorney.</i>

165
00:09:28,276 --> 00:09:30,111
So, I take it
there's absolutely no point

166
00:09:30,153 --> 00:09:32,322
in asking if you'd
like to grab a drink?

167
00:09:32,364 --> 00:09:34,115
I can't,
I have to go over transcripts

168
00:09:34,157 --> 00:09:36,410
for the Fernands case.

169
00:09:36,451 --> 00:09:39,704
You know, if you go somewhere
that's not work or your home

170
00:09:39,746 --> 00:09:41,039
your odds of meeting someone
increase by

171
00:09:41,081 --> 00:09:42,082
like a gazillion percent.

172
00:09:42,123 --> 00:09:43,333
Oh, that's not true.

173
00:09:43,375 --> 00:09:44,918
I could still get mugged
on the way home.

174
00:09:44,959 --> 00:09:48,505
I-In that case, I hope
he's cute and single.

175
00:09:48,547 --> 00:09:50,173
Goodnight, Joanna.

176
00:09:53,218 --> 00:09:56,137
[dramatic music]

177
00:10:17,158 --> 00:10:18,577
Hello, Laurel.

178
00:10:23,373 --> 00:10:24,749
Don't move!

179
00:10:26,543 --> 00:10:27,627
I'm not gonna hurt you.

180
00:10:27,668 --> 00:10:30,255
Stay back. My father's a cop.

181
00:10:30,297 --> 00:10:31,839
You are making a huge mistake.

182
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:33,716
I'm not the person
you think I am.

183
00:10:33,758 --> 00:10:35,218
'And I need your help.'

184
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:37,720
Peter Declan is gonna
be executed in 48 hours.

185
00:10:37,762 --> 00:10:39,639
I think he's innocent.

186
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:42,100
'Declan's wife was gonna blow
the whistle on Jason Brodeur.'

187
00:10:42,142 --> 00:10:43,643
'Brodeur had her murdered.'

188
00:10:43,684 --> 00:10:45,979
There are a thousand lawyers
in Starling City.

189
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:48,815
Why me?

190
00:10:52,860 --> 00:10:54,613
We're both trying to help.

191
00:10:56,197 --> 00:10:59,784
What makes you so sure
I'm gonna help you?

192
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:01,286
Because I know
you'd do anything

193
00:11:01,328 --> 00:11:03,746
to save the life
of an innocent man.

194
00:11:06,333 --> 00:11:08,418
[music continues]

195
00:11:15,342 --> 00:11:17,552
[bell ringing]

196
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:20,597
(Laurel)
'A jury has found you guilty,
Mr. Declan.'

197
00:11:20,639 --> 00:11:22,474
The evidence
was stacked against me

198
00:11:22,516 --> 00:11:24,683
but I didn't kill my wife.

199
00:11:24,725 --> 00:11:27,395
I didn't take my daughter's
mother from her.

200
00:11:29,814 --> 00:11:32,484
The murder weapon was a knife

201
00:11:32,526 --> 00:11:34,944
from your kitchen,
with your prints on it.

202
00:11:34,986 --> 00:11:37,364
'It was found,
along with Camille's blood'

203
00:11:37,405 --> 00:11:39,073
'in the trunk of your car.'

204
00:11:39,115 --> 00:11:41,993
Your neighbors said they heard
an argument that night.

205
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:45,997
We had a knockdown fight
over Jason Brodeur.

206
00:11:46,039 --> 00:11:48,500
Camille worked for him,
and his company had been

207
00:11:48,542 --> 00:11:51,628
dumping toxic waste
into the Glades.

208
00:11:51,670 --> 00:11:54,506
Camille told me that she'd gone
and told a supervisor about it.

209
00:11:54,548 --> 00:11:57,008
I was afraid
for my family's safety.

210
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:59,678
And we argued.

211
00:11:59,718 --> 00:12:02,347
Very loudly. Yes.

212
00:12:02,389 --> 00:12:04,307
Izzy started crying

213
00:12:04,349 --> 00:12:06,685
so Camille went
and stayed in her room.

214
00:12:14,609 --> 00:12:17,945
In the morning,
I went to apologize and uh..

215
00:12:17,987 --> 00:12:19,698
And that's when I found her.

216
00:12:21,658 --> 00:12:23,201
So I just grabbed Izzy

217
00:12:23,243 --> 00:12:26,204
and I ran outside,
and I called 911.

218
00:12:30,875 --> 00:12:33,002
I'm innocent, Ms. Lance.

219
00:12:37,798 --> 00:12:40,260
Well, it looks like someone
forgot a lunch date

220
00:12:40,301 --> 00:12:41,469
with his wife.

221
00:12:41,511 --> 00:12:42,761
What do you mean?

222
00:12:42,803 --> 00:12:44,431
Lunch isn't for another..

223
00:12:45,973 --> 00:12:47,850
...forty-five minutes ago.
I'm so sorry.

224
00:12:47,892 --> 00:12:50,811
It's alright. The restaurant
is holding our table.

225
00:12:50,853 --> 00:12:53,022
Is there something wrong?

226
00:12:53,064 --> 00:12:55,358
Compliance department
has tagged something

227
00:12:55,400 --> 00:12:57,110
$2.6 million withdrawal

228
00:12:57,151 --> 00:12:59,070
'from one of our
Vancouver subsidiaries.'

229
00:12:59,112 --> 00:13:01,197
What, do you mean,
a-are you saying that someone

230
00:13:01,239 --> 00:13:03,575
embezzled $2.6 million
from the company?

231
00:13:03,617 --> 00:13:04,951
Well, it's probably
a bookkeeping error

232
00:13:04,992 --> 00:13:06,994
but, compliance
is understandably

233
00:13:07,036 --> 00:13:08,663
worried about an IRS audit.

234
00:13:08,705 --> 00:13:09,788
Hm.

235
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:14,919
But don't worry.
I'm sure it's nothing.

236
00:13:14,961 --> 00:13:16,504
Oh, come on.
We're gonna be late.

237
00:13:16,546 --> 00:13:17,547
'I mean later.'

238
00:13:17,589 --> 00:13:19,758
[indistinct chatter]

239
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:22,843
Well, I wasn't the lead on this

240
00:13:22,885 --> 00:13:25,513
but from what I recall,
we had fingerprints.

241
00:13:25,555 --> 00:13:28,642
We have blood.
We got motive, everything.

242
00:13:30,935 --> 00:13:32,353
Brodeur seems like
the type of guy

243
00:13:32,395 --> 00:13:35,022
with resources
needed to frame someone.

244
00:13:35,064 --> 00:13:38,192
Laurel, in 24 hours,
Peter Declan is lying down

245
00:13:38,234 --> 00:13:40,111
with a needle in his arm,
he's not getting up.

246
00:13:40,153 --> 00:13:42,113
If I thought for a second,
we didn't have the right guy

247
00:13:42,155 --> 00:13:43,822
do you think there's anything
else I'd be doing right now

248
00:13:43,864 --> 00:13:45,866
except trying to get at
what really happened?

249
00:13:45,908 --> 00:13:48,369
Declan said his wife
went to her supervisor

250
00:13:48,411 --> 00:13:51,122
with allegations that Brodeur
was dumping toxic waste.

251
00:13:51,164 --> 00:13:54,041
Yeah, but that supervisor

252
00:13:54,083 --> 00:13:55,627
he said that never happened.

253
00:13:55,669 --> 00:13:57,044
Let me see.
What was his name?

254
00:13:57,086 --> 00:13:59,046
Here you go.
Istook, Matt Istook.

255
00:13:59,088 --> 00:14:02,175
He said he didn't even
see Camille that day.

256
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:03,468
Happy now?

257
00:14:03,510 --> 00:14:04,636
Yes.

258
00:14:07,764 --> 00:14:09,432
You know, I thought
it'd be a cold day in hell

259
00:14:09,474 --> 00:14:11,225
before you started
defending criminals.

260
00:14:11,267 --> 00:14:13,561
I'm not so sure
Declan's a criminal.

261
