00:28:25,287 --> 00:28:28,123
Tempest purchased a warehouse
in Starling City.

542
00:28:28,165 --> 00:28:31,084
[dramatic music]

543
00:28:35,088 --> 00:28:37,799
- Enough moping.
- Mm.

544
00:28:37,841 --> 00:28:39,343
You quit. It's done.

545
00:28:39,385 --> 00:28:41,136
My advice would be to move on.

546
00:28:41,178 --> 00:28:43,389
Uh, if it were only that easy.

547
00:28:43,430 --> 00:28:44,557
Except it is.

548
00:28:44,598 --> 00:28:46,475
Personal security is dangerous.

549
00:28:46,517 --> 00:28:48,101
Your nephew already
lost his father.

550
00:28:48,143 --> 00:28:50,396
He can't lose his uncle too.

551
00:28:53,023 --> 00:28:54,608
Does it ever bother you
they never caught the guy

552
00:28:54,650 --> 00:28:56,026
who killed Andy?

553
00:28:59,405 --> 00:29:01,407
You know,
when I was in Afghanistan

554
00:29:01,448 --> 00:29:04,201
I had a job, and I did it.

555
00:29:06,036 --> 00:29:07,787
And when I could, I would help
out the people there

556
00:29:07,829 --> 00:29:09,998
so that, in some small way,
when I left

557
00:29:10,040 --> 00:29:12,167
I could believe
I left it a better place.

558
00:29:14,587 --> 00:29:16,004
But ever since I've been home

559
00:29:16,046 --> 00:29:17,964
all I do is protect punks

560
00:29:18,006 --> 00:29:19,216
and spoiled one percenters.

561
00:29:19,258 --> 00:29:21,427
Yeah.

562
00:29:21,468 --> 00:29:23,554
I miss feeling like I'm making
a difference in the world.

563
00:29:23,596 --> 00:29:25,138
Then get out
of personal security

564
00:29:25,180 --> 00:29:26,599
and go do something
you believe in.

565
00:29:26,640 --> 00:29:28,225
- Yeah, what if it's wrong?
- John.

566
00:29:28,267 --> 00:29:30,102
If you believe in something

567
00:29:30,143 --> 00:29:32,688
how can it be wrong?

568
00:29:32,730 --> 00:29:35,649
- 'Jason Brodeur'
- What do you want?

569
00:29:35,691 --> 00:29:37,109
You're gonna confess
that you arranged

570
00:29:37,150 --> 00:29:38,985
to have Peter Declan's wife
murdered.

571
00:29:39,027 --> 00:29:40,820
What, so I can take his place
in prison?

572
00:29:40,862 --> 00:29:43,031
So you can avoid
the death penalty.

573
00:29:43,073 --> 00:29:44,824
Except if I'm dead.

574
00:29:44,866 --> 00:29:46,910
Well, then, you've got no one
to pin Camille's murder on.

575
00:29:46,952 --> 00:29:49,705
'You need me
to exonerate Peter Declan.'

576
00:29:49,747 --> 00:29:50,872
Maybe you could try to force me

577
00:29:50,914 --> 00:29:52,499
to sign a confession
or something.

578
00:29:52,541 --> 00:29:54,000
[screams]

579
00:29:54,042 --> 00:29:55,210
That might be difficult.

580
00:29:55,252 --> 00:29:57,588
[telephone ringing]

581
00:29:57,630 --> 00:29:59,298
'My hand!'

582
00:29:59,339 --> 00:30:02,301
[groaning]

583
00:30:02,342 --> 00:30:05,095
Just answer it.

584
00:30:06,430 --> 00:30:07,973
- What?
- 'It's Ankov.'

585
00:30:08,014 --> 00:30:10,434
'It's going down, one hour.'

586
00:30:10,476 --> 00:30:12,227
What's going down in an hour?

587
00:30:14,313 --> 00:30:15,731
What?

588
00:30:15,773 --> 00:30:17,357
Let's just say..

589
00:30:17,399 --> 00:30:19,610
...Peter Declan's execution

590
00:30:19,652 --> 00:30:22,321
it's getting moved up.

591
00:30:22,362 --> 00:30:23,697
[grunts]

592
00:30:25,532 --> 00:30:26,866
(Laurel)
'Okay, you have to
listen to me.'

593
00:30:26,908 --> 00:30:28,368
We still have a shot.

594
00:30:28,410 --> 00:30:30,036
Do you remember
the friend that I mentioned

595
00:30:30,078 --> 00:30:31,622
the one who believes in you?

596
00:30:31,664 --> 00:30:33,582
He is working on something.

597
00:30:34,916 --> 00:30:36,835
[dramatic music]

598
00:30:39,713 --> 00:30:41,423
I told you

599
00:30:41,465 --> 00:30:44,009
Jason Brodeur is powerful.

600
00:30:49,682 --> 00:30:51,809
Time to unlock the cages.

601
00:30:51,850 --> 00:30:53,143
I've been here before.

602
00:30:53,185 --> 00:30:54,770
These lawyers, holding out

603
00:30:54,812 --> 00:30:56,355
these little nuggets of hope.

604
00:30:58,023 --> 00:30:59,858
[siren blaring]

605
00:30:59,899 --> 00:31:01,819
[indistinct chatter]

606
00:31:08,116 --> 00:31:08,867
What?

607
00:31:13,121 --> 00:31:15,248
(male #1)
'Secure all corners
in cell block C.'

608
00:31:15,290 --> 00:31:18,043
The warden's setting up
a secure perimeter in C block.

609
00:31:18,084 --> 00:31:19,545
'Stay here, Ms. Lance.'

610
00:31:19,586 --> 00:31:20,796
Wait!

611
00:31:22,922 --> 00:31:24,883
[indistinct chatter]

612
00:31:24,924 --> 00:31:26,844
[instrumental music]

613
00:31:28,595 --> 00:31:30,514
[grunting]

614
00:31:34,393 --> 00:31:36,311
[panting]

615
00:31:41,233 --> 00:31:42,442
[screams]

616
00:31:42,484 --> 00:31:43,610
Let's go.

617
00:31:57,583 --> 00:31:58,917
Go, go, go!

618
00:32:07,801 --> 00:32:09,052
Ah!

619
00:32:13,473 --> 00:32:15,392
[grunting]

620
00:32:33,201 --> 00:32:35,328
[panting]

621
00:32:38,039 --> 00:32:39,875
- Open up the generator area.
- Area clear.

622
00:32:39,917 --> 00:32:41,710
Laurel.

623
00:32:41,752 --> 00:32:43,962
(male #2)
'That's right. Stay back.
Area secured.'

624
00:32:44,003 --> 00:32:45,130
(male #3)
'Movin' out.'

625
00:32:54,973 --> 00:32:57,100
[indistinct radio chatter]

626
00:32:58,435 --> 00:33:00,061
Oh, Laurel.

627
00:33:02,063 --> 00:33:03,189
Sweetie.

628
00:33:04,441 --> 00:33:06,318
What are you..

629
00:33:06,359 --> 00:33:08,445
- I'm all right.
- You sure?

630
00:33:08,487 --> 00:33:10,280
I'm sorry about
what I said to you.

631
00:33:10,322 --> 00:33:12,198
You were right, Brodeur's
bodyguard just confessed

632
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:13,617
to Camille Declan's murder.

633
00:33:13,659 --> 00:33:15,744
We got the wrong guy.

634
00:33:15,786 --> 00:33:17,078
Now, listen to me, Laurel.

635
00:33:17,120 --> 00:33:18,705
I'm right too about him.

636
00:33:18,747 --> 00:33:19,915
He's dangerous.

637
00:33:19,957 --> 00:33:21,875
- He's outside the law.
- I know.

638
00:33:24,878 --> 00:33:26,212
He's a killer.

639
00:33:28,423 --> 00:33:30,717
He would have killed that man.

640
00:33:30,759 --> 00:33:33,052
'I looked in his eyes.'

641
00:33:33,094 --> 00:33:35,430
'It's like he had no remorse.'

642
00:33:42,395 --> 00:33:43,522
Hey.

643
00:33:44,606 --> 00:33:46,107
Please.

644
00:33:47,734 --> 00:33:49,361
I'm starving.

645
00:33:50,988 --> 00:33:53,114
I never killed anything before.

646
00:33:54,240 --> 00:33:55,575
[bird chirping]

647
00:34:03,834 --> 00:34:06,753
[dramatic music]

648
00:34:13,635 --> 00:34:15,178
I'm sorry.

649
00:34:18,724 --> 00:34:19,683
[bird shrieks]

650
00:34:31,611 --> 00:34:33,697
(Quentin)
'Let's get you home, sweetie.'

651
00:34:33,739 --> 00:34:36,282
How'd he get into
that prison anyway, huh?

652
00:34:36,324 --> 00:34:39,452
A grown man in an outfit,
and a hood

653
00:34:39,494 --> 00:34:41,496
that kind of stands out
a little, doesn't it?

654
00:34:41,538 --> 00:34:43,665
He actually wasn't
wearing the outfit this time.

655
00:34:43,707 --> 00:34:46,167
He was in a prison-guard uniform

656
00:34:46,209 --> 00:34:47,753
and a ski mask.

657
00:34:50,547 --> 00:34:51,924
- What?
- 'Nothing.'

658
00:34:51,965 --> 00:34:54,133
I just had an idea.

659
00:34:54,175 --> 00:34:55,802
'Get in the car.'

660
00:35:20,118 --> 00:35:21,078
[door beeps]

661
00:35:27,667 --> 00:35:28,627
[door beeps]

662
00:35:33,757 --> 00:35:34,716
[door beeps]

663
00:35:40,055 --> 00:35:41,180
[door opens]

664
00:35:47,729 --> 00:35:50,649
[instrumental music]

665
00:36:09,793 --> 00:36:11,461
Okay.

666
00:36:11,503 --> 00:36:13,922
Here's the security footage from
the Exchange building shooting

667
00:36:13,964 --> 00:36:15,465
but I've already scrubbed
through all of it.

668
00:36:15,507 --> 00:36:17,175
Yeah? Well,
we're gonna do it again.

669
00:36:18,593 --> 00:36:19,970
So, listen, when you went
through the camera

670
00:36:20,012 --> 00:36:21,346
security tapes,
you were looking for a guy

671
00:36:21,387 --> 00:36:22,722
in a green outfit
and a green hood, right?

672
00:36:22,764 --> 00:36:23,932
What do you want me to look for

673
00:36:23,974 --> 00:36:26,184
a man in a wig and a tutu?

674
00:36:26,225 --> 00:36:28,061
I want you to look for anything
that's out of the ordinary.

675
00:36:28,103 --> 00:36:29,646
Okay? Just look.

676
00:36:37,320 --> 00:36:38,864
Hey, whoa, whoa, whoa.
Wait. Wait. Go back ten seconds.

677
00:36:38,905 --> 00:36:40,032
What is that?

678
00:36:43,284 --> 00:36:45,037
'I'll be damned.'

679
00:36:47,580 --> 00:36:49,041
Play that again.

680
00:36:52,335 --> 00:36:55,588
- Thank you, Laurel.
- Don't thank me.

681
00:36:55,630 --> 00:36:58,967
Thank Brodeur's bodyguard
Ankov for flipping him.

682
00:37:00,593 --> 00:37:03,013
'I think there's someone
that wants to see you.'

683
00:37:03,055 --> 00:37:04,347
Izzy.

684
00:37:20,155 --> 00:37:23,075
(man on TV)
'At least five federal, state,
and local agencies'

685
00:37:23,116 --> 00:37:25,077
'are seeking millions of dollars
in fines'

686
00:37:25,118 --> 00:37:26,786
'and environmental
cleanup costs'

687
00:37:26,828 --> 00:37:29,414
'from Brodeur Chemical.'

688
00:37:29,455 --> 00:37:30,916
'New facts have come to light'

689
00:37:30,957 --> 00:37:33,919
'that Brodeur Chemical employee,
Camille Declan'

690
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:37,130
'had discovered Brodeur
was illegally disposing waste'

691
00:37:37,172 --> 00:37:38,840
'and had collected
a file of evidence'

692
00:37:38,882 --> 00:37:42,802
'against her employer,
before her murder in 2007.'

693
00:37:42,844 --> 00:37:45,805
'Peter Declan, who was
convicted of killing his wife'

694
00:37:45,847 --> 00:37:48,767
'has been released,
and the case has been reopened.'

695
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:04,199
<i>Shengcun.</i>

696
00:38:05,200 --> 00:38:06,868
Yeah.

697
00:38:06,910 --> 00:38:08,745
Bird. I know.

698
00:38:08,787 --> 00:38:12,207
<i>Shengcun</i> not mean "bird."</i>

699
00:38:12,249 --> 00:38:14,584
<i>Shengcun</i> mean "survive."</i>

700
00:38:15,752 --> 00:38:17,921
You speak English?

701
00:38:17,963 --> 00:38:19,965
You want survive this place

702
00:38:21,091 --> 00:38:23,843
bird not last thing you kill.

703
00:38:28,890 --> 00:38:31,184
And forget her.

704
00:38:31,226 --> 00:38:33,812
'You look at that all day'

705
00:38:33,853 --> 00:38:36,606
you not survive this place.

706
00:38:43,071 --> 00:38:45,991
[dramatic music]

707
00:38:52,413 --> 00:38:53,957
You wanted to see me?

708
00:38:55,708 --> 00:38:57,252
You look nervous, Moira.

709
00:38:58,295 --> 00:39:00,046
Do I have a reason to be?

710
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:02,757
We all do.

711
00:39:09,889 --> 00:39:12,809
A modern-day Robin hood.

712
00:39:12,851 --> 00:39:15,770
What, are you worried that your
net worth makes you a target?

713
00:39:18,190 --> 00:39:20,275
Jason Brodeur.

714
00:39:20,317 --> 00:39:21,943
Adam Hunt.

715
00:39:21,985 --> 00:39:23,903
Warren Patel.

716
00:39:23,945 --> 00:39:26,198
Tell me you see a connection,
Moira.

717
00:39:26,239 --> 00:39:27,699
He's not targeting the rich.

718
00:39:27,740 --> 00:39:29,826
'No, he's not.'

719
00:39:29,868 --> 00:39:31,494
He's targeting the list.

720
00:39:39,169 --> 00:39:40,795
(Oliver)
'You here
for the bodyguard position?'

721
00:39:40,837 --> 00:39:43,840
'Cause the new guy just quit.

722
00:39:43,882 --> 00:39:45,008
No, I'm not.

723
00:39:46,592 --> 00:39:48,345
I'm here about
the other position.

724
00:39:51,306 --> 00:39:53,641
Just to be clear..

725
00:39:53,683 --> 00:39:55,977
...I'm not signing on
to be a sidekick.

726
00:39:56,019 --> 00:39:57,896
But you're right.

727
00:39:57,937 --> 00:39:59,314
Fighting for this city
needs to be done

728
00:39:59,356 --> 00:40:00,857
and you're gonna do this
with or without me.

729
00:40:00,899 --> 00:40:02,359
Yeah.

730
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:04,194
But with me,
there'll be fewer casualties

731
00:40:04,236 --> 00:40:05,611
including you.

732
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:08,907
Diggle, I'm not looking
for anybody to save me.

733
00:40:08,948 --> 00:40:10,992
Maybe not..

734
00:40:11,034 --> 00:40:13,452
...but you need someone
just the same.

735
00:40:13,494 --> 00:40:15,372
'You are fighting a war, Queen'

736
00:40:15,413 --> 00:40:18,291
'except you have no idea
what war does to you'

737
00:40:18,333 --> 00:40:21,460
how it scrapes off
little pieces of your soul.

738
00:40:23,380 --> 00:40:26,174
And you need someone
to remind you

739
00:40:26,216 --> 00:40:27,592
of who you are

740
00:40:27,633 --> 00:40:29,386
not this thing you're becoming.

741
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,395
- 'Oliver Queen.'
- What is this?

742
00:40:38,436 --> 00:40:40,021
- You can't just barge in here.
- Yeah?

743
00:40:40,063 --> 00:40:41,981
Well, I got a badge and a gun
